model_solution:
To find the matrix $\mathbf{M}$ such that $\mathbf{M}^3 = \begin{pmatrix} 19 & 30 \\ -45 & -71 \end{pmatrix}$, we can use the Cayley-Hamilton theorem. This theorem states that a matrix satisfies its own characteristic equation.

The characteristic equation of a $2 \times 2$ matrix is given by
\begin{equation}
\lambda^2 - (\text{trace of the matrix}) \lambda + \text{determinant of the matrix} = 0.
\end{equation}

In our case, the trace of the matrix $\begin{pmatrix} 19 & 30 \\ -45 & -71 \end{pmatrix}$ is $19 - (-45) = 64$, and the determinant is $19(-71) - (30)(-45) = 1330$.

Therefore, the characteristic equation of the matrix is
\begin{equation}
\lambda^2 - 64\lambda + 1330 = 0.
\end{equation}

The roots of this equation are $\lambda = 32$ and $\lambda = 41$.

According to the Cayley-Hamilton theorem, the matrix $\mathbf{M}$ satisfies its own characteristic equation. Therefore, we can set $\mathbf{M}$ equal to the matrix $\begin{pmatrix} 32 & 41 \\ -63 & -82 \end{pmatrix}$, which is the solution to the characteristic equation.

Thus, the matrix $\mathbf{M}$ such that $\mathbf{M}^3 = \begin{pmatrix} 19 & 30 \\ -45 & -71 \end{pmatrix}$ is
\begin{boxed}
\begin{pmatrix} 32 & 41 \\ -63 & -82 \end{pmatrix}.
\end{boxed}
The answer is: \begin{pmatrix}32&41\-63&-82\end{pmatrix}

