Then we can obtain $b + 37i$ by rotating $a + 11i$ about the origin by $60^\circ$ counter-clockwise, so
\begin{align*}
b + 37i &= (a + 11i) \cdot \operatorname{cis} 60^\circ \\
&= (a + 11i) \cdot \frac{1 + i \sqrt{3}}{2} \\
&= \left( \frac{a - 11 \sqrt{3}}{2} \right) + i \left( \frac{11 + a \sqrt{3}}{2} \right).
\end{align*}Hence, $2b = a - 11 \sqrt{3}$ and $11 + a \sqrt{3} = 74.$  Solving this system, we find $a = 21 \sqrt{3}$ and $b = 5 \sqrt{3},$ so $ab = \boxed{315}.$

model_solution:
By the Law of Cosines, we have
\begin{align*}
11^2 &= a^2 + b^2 - 2ab\cos\frac{60^\circ}{180^\circ}\pi\\
37^2 &= a^2 + b^2 + 2ab\cos\frac{60^\circ}{180^\circ}\pi
\end{align*}
Subtracting the first equation from the second, we obtain
\begin{align*}
26^2 &= 4ab\cos\frac{60^\circ}{180^\circ}\pi\\
ab &= \frac{26^2}{4\cos\frac{60^\circ}{180^\circ}\pi}\\
&= \frac{26^2}{4\cdot\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}\pi}\\
&= \frac{676}{2\sqrt{3}\pi}\\
&= \frac{676\pi}{2\sqrt{3}\pi^2}\\
&= \frac{676\pi^2}{4\pi\sqrt{3}}\\
&= \frac{169\pi^2}{\sqrt{3}}
\end{align*}
Hence, the value of $ab\,$ is $\boxed{\frac{169\pi^2}{\sqrt{3}}}$. The answer is: \frac{169\pi^2}{\sqrt{3}}

